solutions.content:
Intuitions:
- if K === 0, no moves can be made
- if K >= 2, any permutation of characters is possible with enough steps
	- The JS Array.sort() method already sorts lexically
- If K === 1 then the answer will be a rotation of the string
	- You can build these strings from splitting and concatenating S, but that would be wasteful when all we are about is the character code values

Method:
- if K === 0, return S
- if K >= 2, 
	- .split('') the string into its characters
	- .sort() the resulting array (defaults to ascending order anyway)
	- .join('') the characters
	- return the concatenated string
- If K === 1
	- iterate over all possible rotations of the string, compared to the rotation at 0 (the original string)
		- iterate over and compare all characters in those strings, once 2 different characters are found: 
			- if the new string character is "smaller", update the result to the new starting index
			- move on to the next rotation

Instead of building these rotations for comparison, it is much easier on the memory to store the starting indices and add integers from [0, string.length) when comparing characters.
> (Base Index + Number of Same Characters) % String Length = The Index in the "Rotated" String

```
var orderlyQueue = function(S, K) {
	if (K === 0) return S;
    else if (K > 1) return S.split('').sort().join('');

	let result = 0, L = S.length;

	for (let i = 1; i < L; i++) {
        for (let j = 0; j < L; j++) {
			let d = S.charCodeAt((result + j) % L) - S.charCodeAt((i + j) % L);
			if (d !== 0)  {
				if (d > 0) result = i;
				break;
			}
		}
	}

	return S.slice(result) + S.slice(0, result);

};

```

