solutions.content:
**Given a string xbqca and k =1.**
the choices we have are xbqca,  bqcax, qcaxb, caxbq, axbqc
the only option we have is to take the first char and append it to last because k is 1 so we are only allowed to chose form the first 1 characters of the string, so we are not having much choice there other that taking the first char.

One way to find the lexographically smallest is by finding all the rotations of string xbqca and and comparing with each other this would take TC O(n^2)  because of n strings and n-1 comparisons resulting in
 n*(n-1) => O(n)

Can we do the same in a better way?
For the given string xbqca the lexographically smallest rotation is axbqc 
For cba it is acb

notice the ans starts with the  smallest character 
So if we find the smallest character in string then we can find the ans.
given string "bcaqd" with length n smallest char is a at index 2 now, 
substring(2, n)+ substring(0, 2) gives "aqdbc" which is the answer.
this can be done in O(n)

what if there is character repetition? we need to account for that
Given string "bdatuaz" of length 7, smallest char a is at index 2 and 5, 
In this case we have to finalize on an index by checking the character next to index
In this case we check  the character at index 3 't' and index 6 'z' , as char 't' at index 2+1 is less than char 'z' at index 5+1 we take the smallest index as 2 and ignore 5.
now answer would be  substring(2, n)+ substring(0, 2)
                                         "atuaz"       +  "bd"     = "atuazbd"

**For the case k> 1.**
Let "xbqca" be the given string and k = 2
"xbqca"  we take 'b' from first 2 characters and append to end =>    "xqcab"
"xqcab"   take q                                                                         =>    "xcabq"
"xcabq"   take c                                                                         =>     "xabqc"
"xabqc"   take x                                                                         =>     "abqcx"
 "abqcx"  take a                                                                        =>       "bqcxa"
 "bqcxa"   take b                                                                         =>     "qcxab"
 "qcxab"  take c                                                                        =>       "qxabc"
  "qxabc"  take q                                                                        =>       "xabcq"
   "xabcq"  take x                                                                        =>       "abcqx"

finally we end up with a string sorted by its characters. which is the lexographically smallest possible.
Now consider same string "xbqca" with k = 3
"xbqca"  we take 'b' from first 3 characters and append to end =>    "xqcab"
"xqcab"   take c                                                                         =>    "xqabc"
"xqabc"   take q                                                                         =>    "xabcq"
"xabcq"   take x                                                                         =>    "abcqx"

again we end up with a string sorted by its chars which is the lexographically smallest.

so fro any k>1 we can reach the lexographically smallest string possible (sorted string).
This is possible because we are allowed to make the append operation any number of times.

So for inputs with k>1 ans is simply the sorted string.
now the TC of sorting normally is O(nlogn) but here it given characters can only be lower case letters 
which is total 26.

to sort string "debbc" we create an  array arr of size 26 
itereate the string for each char ch  arr[ch]++;
after first iteration we get a frequency arr   a b c d e f -  - - z
                                                                    0 2 1 1 10        0
now we create ans ="" and iterrate arr form i =0 to 26
we append each char 'a'+i  arr[i] number of times

ans would be ""+b+b+c+d+e = "bbcde"
Sorting also done in O(n) and constant space

```
class Solution {  //O(n) time and O(1) space
    public String orderlyQueue(String s, int k) {
        int n = s.length();
        if(k ==1)
            return smallestRotated(s);
        return sorted(s);
    }

    //O(n) time, O(1) space
    public String smallestRotated(String s){
        char smallest = s.charAt(0);
        int smallIndex = 0;
        int n = s.length();
        for(int i =0; i<s.length(); i++){
            if(s.charAt(i)< smallest){         // new smallest found
                smallest = s.charAt(i);
                smallIndex = i;
            }else if(s.charAt(i) == smallest){   // already existing smallest with a different index (repetition)
                int j = 0;
                for(j =1; j<s.length(); j++){
                    char next1 = s.charAt((i+j)%n);                              // trying to compare next chars 
                    char next2 = s.charAt((smallIndex+j)%n);
                    if(next1< smallest){                                            // the next char happens to be the smaller than
                        smallest = s.charAt(i+j);                                // current smallest then updating it as smallest
                        smallIndex = i+j;
                        break;
                    }
                    if(next1< next2){                                               // comparing next chars of two index
                        smallIndex = i;                                              
                        break;
                    }else if(next2< next1)
                        break;
                }
                i = i+j;  
            }
        }
        return s.substring(smallIndex, n)+s.substring(0, smallIndex);
    }

    //O(n) time, O(1) space only constant space used
    public String sorted(String s){
        int[] arr = new int[26];
        for(char ch: s.toCharArray()){                                                   // creating char freq table
            arr[ch-'a']++;
        }
        StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder();
        char ch = 'a';
        for(int val: arr){                                                                       // using char freq table to get the sorted array
            while(val-- >0)
                sb.append(ch);
            ch++;
        }
        return sb.toString();
    }
}
```

