# Explanation
 ***This question is similar to array rotation***
1.  (k==1), we can rotate the array everytime and get the lexicographically Smallest string
2.  k>1), this means that we can swap any adjacent two characters in the string
	*     Actually, when K>=2, we can prove that we can use the first 2 elements as a buffer to swap any two adjacent    characters. 
	*     Assume that we want to swap S[i] and S[i+1], we can first pop first i-1 characters to the end, then pop i+1              and i, finally pop i+2~end.
3. Since we can reach any permutation by swapping adjacent characters (like bubble sort), in this case the minimal reachable permutation is the sorted String. So when k>1 , solution is sorted string

```
string orderlyQueue(string S, int K) {
        if(K==1){ //rotate string to get all permutations and take lexographically smallest string
            int n=S.size();
            string smallest=S;
            for(int i=1;i<n;i++){
                char ch=S[0];
                S.erase(S.begin());
                S.push_back(ch);

                if(S<smallest)
                    smallest=S;

            }
            return smallest;
        }
        //else
        //k>1 means we can swap any two adjacent characters(as mentioned in step 2). 
        //We can sort the entire string (as we have infinite moves ),similar to what we do in BUBBLE SORT
        //So final answer will be sortedString

        sort(S.begin(),S.end());
        return S;

    }

