***INTUITION:-***
We should think this question considering k = 1 first.
So given a string with k = 1, then by removing first k characters and putting them at string end, you are effectively rotating the string. Here in different moves you will be generating the rotated string.

Thus for k = 1, we rotate the given string character by character until we got original string back. At every move we put the rotated string into a vector of string. After getting all rotated string into vector of string, we sort the vector and the string at index 0 will be our required string.

Now the second case to be considered is that if K is greater than 1.
If you take any string with k greater than 1, you will find that you are able to generate all the permutation of the string. Among all the permutaion we will return the smallest string.
No need to generate all the permutation just sort the given string and return it.

***Example for k > 1***
let string s = "rao", and k = 2
the possible string that can be obtained using the given rule are, rao->aor->oar->ora->aro->roa
which all are permutaion of the given string.

```
class Solution {
public:
    string orderlyQueue(string S, int K) {
        int n = S.length();

        if(n == 0){
            return "";
        }

        if(K > 1){
            sort(S.begin(),S.end());
            return S;
        }

        vector<string> v;

        for(int i=0;i<n;i++){

            char curr = S[0];
            S.erase(S.begin());
            S += curr;
            v.push_back(S);

        }

        sort(v.begin(),v.end());

        return v[0];
    }
};
```

