# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
First thought that comes in mind is that you should append letters such that we attain string closest to sorted string.
And if we see that for k = 1 we can only rotate whole string but for k > 1 we can do other things and change its order of letters.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
### Case 1 --> k = 1
-> we will rotate string and find the smallest string.
##### Execution
=> append the whole string s, so that it is easy to access rotated elements.
=> check for each substring of size n in s for smallest sub string.
```
eg) cbaad -> 0 - index
=> cbaadcbaad.
=> for i = 2 we have substring aadcb which is smalles substring.
=> it can be obtained by appending b and then c.
```

### Case 2 --> k > 1
-> we can change order of adjacent letters by using first 2 letters as a buffer.
-> fix the first letter
-> rotate string from i = 1. (0 - index string s)
-> rotate till adjacent letter is not at the last position.
-> when adjacent letter is at the last position we have order of adjacent letters reversed.
-> similarly we can just sort the string.
##### Execution
=> sort the string
```
eg) cbaad
=> fix c and rotate from b.
=> finally obtain => cdaab.
=> rotate => bcdaa. (order changed => cb -> bc)
```
# Complexity
- Time complexity:- O(n log(n))
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    string orderlyQueue(string s, int k) {
        int n = s.size();
        string sorted = s;
        sort(sorted.begin(), sorted.end());
        if(k > 1)
        {
            return sorted;
        }
        string ans = s;
        s += s;
        for(int i = 0; i < n; i ++)
        {
            ans = min(ans, s.substr(i, n));
        }
        return ans;
    }
};
```

