# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
My first intuition was that the no. of insertions needed to make the string palindromic would be **same as the no. of deletions** required to make the string palindromic. suppose we have the string ***abbca***. 

Either we can add c to make it palindromic ***acbbca*** or we can remove c to make it palindromic ***abba***.

Now the question has reduced to [Find the Longest Palindromic subsequence](https://leetcode.com/problems/longest-palindromic-subsequence/description/). Then subtract the length of LPS from the actual length of the string.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
In the above example :
- length of the LPS -> ***abba*** = 4
- length of the actual string ***abbca*** = 5
- ans -> 5 - 4 = 1

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
we are iterating the string n times for each character. So the time complexity would be $$O(n^2)$$.

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
We are using 2D array for DP. So the space complexity is $$O(n^2)$$.
It can further be reduced to $$O(n)$$ as for a particular moment we are just using the above row to make use to DP. We just need to rows instead of the whole DP array. *For the sake for simplicity I have used 2D array (you can try and further optimise it to $$O(n)$$).*

# Code
```
class Solution {

    public int solve(String s) {
        int[][] dp = new int[s.length() + 1][s.length() + 1];
        String sr = (new StringBuilder(s)).reverse().toString();

        for(int i = 1; i <= s.length(); i++) {
            for(int j = 1; j <= s.length(); j++) {
                char a = s.charAt(i - 1);
                char b = sr.charAt(j - 1);
                if(a == b) {
                    dp[i][j] = dp[i - 1][j - 1] + 1;
                } else {
                    dp[i][j] = Math.max(dp[i - 1][j], dp[i][j - 1]);
                }
            }
        }
        return dp[s.length()][s.length()];
    }

    public int minInsertions(String s) {
        return s.length() - solve(s);
    }
}
```

