solutions.content:
Denote `dp[i][j]` as the minimum number of insertions we need to make `s[i..j]` a palindrome. For chars at two ends, if they are the same, no further insertion needed. Otherwise, we just ignore any one of the ends and insert the same char as the other one in order to make `s[i...j-1]` or `s[i+1...j]` a palindrome. That is how we solve a problem with its subproblem.

Thus, based on the analysis above, we have transition function for this dynamic programming problem is
```
if s[i] == s[j]:
    dp[i][j] = dp[i+1][j-1]
else:
    dp[i][j] = min(dp[i+1][j] + 1, dp[i][j-1] + 1)
```

The code in Java is in following segment. Note that our method is **from a short substring to longer one**. So the nested loop should handle to indecies in opposite ways or control the loop with starting point and size of substring. 

```
class Solution {
    public int minInsertions(String s) {
        int n = s.length();
        int[][] dp = new int[n][n];
        for(int j = 1; j < n; j++) {
            for(int i = j-1; i >= 0; i--) {
                if(s.charAt(i) == s.charAt(j)) {
                    if(j - i <= 1)
                        dp[i][j] = 0;   // Two adjasent chars are the same. No insertion needed.
                    else
                        dp[i][j] = dp[i+1][j-1];
                } else {
                    dp[i][j] = Math.min(dp[i+1][j] + 1, dp[i][j-1] + 1);
                }
            }
        }
        return dp[0][n-1];
    }
}
```

