# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
Think of applying Longest Common Subsequence to it


# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
Take a string, then reverse it 
Now, for string to be a palindrome, the original and reversed string should be equal


Now observe that when you remove longest common subsequence of both strings(orginal and reversed string) you will be left with characters that are not forming a palindrome i.e we need to insert the copy of these left characters to original string to make it a plaindrome

# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(mn)
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

    Where m:length of string
          n:length of reversed string
- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
    public int minInsertions(String s) {
        String s1 = "";
        for(int i=0;i<s.length();i++){
            s1 = s.charAt(i) + s1;
        }
        int lcs = lcs(s1,s,s.length(),s.length());

        // Main Logic //

        return s.length()-lcs;

        //            // 

    }
    public int lcs(String str1, String str2, int m, int n){
        int[][] dp = new int[m+1][n+1];
        for(int i=0;i<=m;i++){
            for(int j=0;j<=n;j++){
                if(i==0||j==0) dp[i][j]=0;
            }
        }
        for(int i=1;i<=m;i++){
            for(int j=1;j<=n;j++){
                if(str1.charAt(i-1)==str2.charAt(j-1))
                    dp[i][j] = 1 + dp[i-1][j-1];
                else{
                    dp[i][j] = Math.max(dp[i-1][j],dp[i][j-1]);
                }
            }
        }
        return dp[m][n];
    }
}
```

