solutions.content:
We are given, `encoded[i] = array[i]^array[i+1]`
Now, for the first element, `encoded[0] = array[0]^array[1] `(`array[0]` has been given to us as `'first'`)
So, `encoded[0] = first^array[1]`
Taking `^` with first on both sides,
`first^encoded[0] = first^first^array[1]`
=> `array[1] = first^encoded[0]`
Similarly, `array[2] = array[1]^encoded[1]`, But we can reduce this to the following code-

```
loop(i, n){
array[i+1] = first^encoded[i];
first = array[i+1];
}
```

This can be further reduced to one-liner in CPP using vectors.
Final Code: 
```
class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> decode(vector<int>& encoded, int first) {
        vector<int> ans{first};
        for(int x: encoded)
            ans.push_back(first^=x);
        return ans;
    }
};
```

